# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australia-national-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The **1912 Triangular Tournament** was a Test cricket competition played between Australia, England and South Africa, the only Test-playing nations at the time.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The ultimate winners of the tournament were England, with four wins in their six matches, but the tournament was deemed a failure, with disappointing crowds and uncompetitive cricket, caused in part by a weakened Australia team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was the first tournament in Test history to be played between more than two nations.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] It was the only such tournament until the Asian Test Championships of 1998–99 and 2001–02, and the ICC World Test Championship which began in 2019.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a competition involving all three of the nations then playing Test cricket (Australia, England and South Africa) was proposed at the first meeting of the Imperial Cricket Conference in July 1909.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The original proposal was for a tournament to be held every four years, with the first hosted by England in 1912.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] For a variety of reasons, the tournament was not a success.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The summer was one of the wettest since records began in 1766: rainfall in the three months of June, July and August was more than twice the seasonal average, and August, 1912, was the coolest, dullest and wettest August of the 20th century.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] At that time, pitches were not covered to protect them against rain, so the batsmen were at a distinct disadvantage on the proverbial sticky wicket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] These problems were exacerbated since Tests in England were in those days played over three days rather than the five days that is now usual.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] In addition, disputes between the players and management in Australia meant that six leading Australian players refused to tour whilst medical duties meant “Ranji” Hordern, easily Australia’s best bowler in the 1911–12 Ashes series, could not tour either.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] These setbacks severely weakened a team that had otherwise been level with England in recent Ashes series.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The leg spin and googly bowlers in the South African team were very effective on the matting pitches then in use in South Africa, but were less deadly on English grass pitches.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] As a result, England dominated, winning four of their six matches and drawing the other two.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The tournament was so unsuccessful that it has never been repeated.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The idea of a tournament of international cricket matches between more than two countries was not repeated, outside of regional tournaments in East Africa and the West Indies, until the invention of One Day International cricket and the first Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] The only other Test cricket tournaments in history were the Asian Test Championships played in 1998–99 and 2001–02, which were also not great successes, until the ICC World Test Championship began in 2019.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1912-triangular-tournament] Perhaps the most notable incident of the series was Australian bowler Jimmy Matthews taking two hat-tricks in the same Test match, one in each innings of the opening match against South Africa, the only time a bowler has taken two hat-tricks in the same Test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1969–70 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was a List A tournament took place from November 1969 to January 1970.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] It was the first season of the Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing the six states in Australia, and a New Zealand team, took part in the competition in a knockout format.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 22 November 1969 when Victoria took on Tasmania at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After five matches were played, the final took place on 1 January 1970 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Victoria and New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] After winning the toss, Victoria were bowled out for 129, with New Zealand chasing the total down with six wickets to spare.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1969-70-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The first season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at domestic level.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The **1970–71 Vehicle & General Australasian knock-out competition** was the second edition of the official List A domestic tournament in Australia.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Seven teams representing six states in Australia and New Zealand took part in the knock-out competition.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The competition began on 18 October 1970 when South Australia took on Victoria at the Adelaide Oval.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The 1970–71 cup final was played on 6 February 1971 at the Melbourne Cricket Ground between Queensland and Western Australia, with Western Australia recording an 91 run victory over Queensland.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] Ian Chappell scored the most runs in the tournament with 176 runs with Graham McKenzie from Western Australia taking the most wickets with eight.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1970-71-vehicle-general-australasian-knock-out-competition] The second season of the competition was a straight knockout competition between the six states of Australia and a team that represented New Zealand at the domestic level.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The **1975 Cricket World Cup Final** was a One Day International cricket match played at Lord's, London, on 21 June 1975 to determine the winner of the 1975 Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] It was the second time that the West Indies and Australia had met in the tournament, after playing against each other in the group stage.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The West Indies won the match by 17 runs to claim their first title.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] West Indies qualified for the knockouts with a first-place finish in Group B.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The team won all three of their matches against Australia, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then in the semi-final against New Zealand, the opposition opened brilliantly, but when Glenn Turner fell, the wickets tumbled the West Indies scored the required 158 to reach the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia made it through to the knockouts in second place with their only loss being against the West Indies.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] But they did defeat Pakistan and Sri Lanka to take on England in the semi-final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Gary Gilmour took six wickets in the English innings to help them through to the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first final was played on 21 June (Midsummer of that year), a sunny day, in front of a capacity crowd of 26,765.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia won the toss and invited the West Indies to bat, hoping to make use of ideal bowling conditions.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The first moment of drama came when opener Roy Fredericks was dismissed hit wicket; he hooked a bouncer from Dennis Lillee for six, but in his follow-through lost his balance and knocked the bails off the stumps.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were on top at 50/3 when West Indian captain Clive Lloyd came to the crease in partnership with veteran Rohan Kanhai.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The pair swung the match in the West Indies' favour by putting on 149 for the fourth wicket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai played the anchor role – not scoring for 11 overs – while Lloyd took on the Australian bowling attack, surviving a dropped catch on 26 to score a century off 82 balls with 12 fours and two sixes, being dismissed shortly afterwards for 102.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Kanhai, in what would be his farewell from international cricket, scored an invaluable 55.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Solid contributions from Keith Boyce and Bernard Julien helped the West Indies close their innings at 291/8.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Burly left-arm seamer Gary Gilmour was the pick of the Australian bowlers with 5/48, backing up his strong semi-final performance.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The Australian run chase began steadily: at the 20-over mark, they were 80/1 with Alan Turner and captain Ian Chappell taking advantage of an easy pitch and fast outfield.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Then Viv Richards, who had failed with the bat, left his mark on the match with the next three run-outs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] First he swooped in and dismissed Turner with a direct hit from close range, then Greg Chappell was also out with a direct hit after a slight misfield.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Doug Walters came in and helped his captain steady the ship.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Australia were at 162/3 with 21 overs remaining when Chappell, facing his opposing captain, pushed a ball to the left of mid-wicket and started off for a run.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] He hesitated initially when he saw Richards approaching but started off again after Richards fumbled the ball, only to be caught short of the crease by Richards' lightning recovery and return to Lloyd at the bowler's end.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] In each situation, the batsmen probably would have made the run had they not hesitated.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When Lillee joined Jeff Thomson as last man in, Australia required 59 runs to win off seven overs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The duo kept the game alive, putting on an unlikely last-wicket stand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] With three overs remaining Lillee hit a no-ball to Fredericks at extra cover off Vanburn Holder and the crowd rushed on to the field oblivious to the umpire's call.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Amid the chaos, Fredericks attempted a run-out but missed and the ball disappeared into the crowd.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Lillee and Thomson kept running between the wickets until the crowd was dispersed.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When play was resumed, the umpires decided to give Australia two runs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] After protest from Thomson, they awarded three runs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The match finally ended three balls later after Thomson had run a leg bye and Lillee scored a single.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The final wicket fell with Thomson swinging wildly and missing.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Having not realised the wicket-keeper had held the ball Thomson set off for a run, attempted to return after recognising his mistake but not before Murray knocked the bails off with a well-aimed underarm throw with his gloves on for a run-out.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] The game ended at 8:43 pm after nearly 10 hours play.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Another pitch invasion ensued as the players and umpires ran for safety, with Thomson having his cricket pads stolen, Boyce losing his shoes and umpire Bird having his hat taken.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] Bird later said that he came across the stolen hat being worn by a bus conductor in London a year after the event.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup-final] When he asked about it, he was told by the conductor, who did not recognise Bird, that he'd "won the race" by sprinting onto the field at the final to take it.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The **1975 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '75**) was the inaugural men's Cricket World Cup, and the first major tournament in the history of One Day International (ODI) cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference (ICC), it took place in England, between 7 June and 21 June 1975.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was sponsored by Prudential Assurance Company and had eight participating countries: the six Test-playing teams of the time – Australia, England, India, New Zealand, Pakistan, the West Indies – and the two leading Associate nations at the time – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The teams were divided into two groups of four, with each team playing each other in their group once; the top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals, with the winners of these matches meeting in the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match consisted of 60 overs per side and was played in traditional white clothing and with red balls; all were played and ended in daylight.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] England and New Zealand finished as the top two teams in Group A, while the West Indies finished top of the Group B table ahead of Australia as the four teams qualified through to the semi-finals.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia defeated England and the West Indies defeated New Zealand in the semi-finals, the West Indies which came into the tournament as favourites, defeated Australia in the final at Lord's by 17 runs to become the first World Cup winners.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] New Zealand batsman, Glenn Turner was the top run-scorer for the tournament with 333 runs, whilst Australian bowler Gary Gilmour was the top wicket-taker with 11 wickets despite only playing in the final two matches.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first multilateral cricket competition at international level was the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was played between the three test nations at the time – England, Australia and South Africa.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The concept was later dropped because of inclement weather and a lack of public interest.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first one-day match to occur was in 1962 when four English county cricket teams filled in a gap to play in a limited overs knockout competition.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was won by Northamptonshire who defeated Leicestershire by five wickets.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The limited-over format had been used in what sponsors marketed as a 'World Cricket Cup' in England in 1966 and 1967, contested between England, a Rest of the World XI, and a touring team (the West Indies in 1966 and Pakistan in 1967).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The marketing of the event was clearly influenced by the hosting of the 1966 FIFA World Cup in the same country.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The 1966 'World Cricket Cup' was won by England, that in 1967 by the Rest of the World.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] A report in the *Cricketer* implied that the last such match in this "Triangular Tournament", between Pakistan and the Rest of the World was neither well-attended nor taken entirely seriously: "It was a pity that a larger crowd was not present ...
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Sobers took the Cup and the World Xl took the gold medals.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] It was not until 1971 that the first official One Day International (ODI) took place at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) as a replacement for the third test of the 1970–71 Ashes series between Australia and England.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to a deluge of rain that had affected the match for the first three days of the test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match was a forty over match with each over being eight deliveries.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After England made 190 from 39.4 overs, Australia chased the target at a steady rate to secure the match with 42 balls remaining.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Two years later at Lord's during the 1973 Women's Cricket World Cup, plans were made for a men's tournament to take place in 1975.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was planned to involve all the Test nations at the time in two group stages with the top two in each group qualifying for the knockout stage with the final at Lord's.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The format of the 1975 Cricket World Cup had the eight teams split into two groups of four, with each team playing the others in their group once.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played over 60 overs per side with group stage matches scheduled to take place between 7 and 14 June.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Each match was played entirely during day, with a cut off time of 7.30 pm.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Three days were allocated to each match with each able to be continued if they were halted for rain or bad light.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group advanced to the semi-finals on 18 June, with the winners qualifying for the final at Lord's on 21 June.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight teams were invited to compete at the World Cup: the six full members of the International Cricket Conference (ICC), and two other teams – Sri Lanka and East Africa.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] South Africa was not allowed to complete due to the sporting boycott of the country which took place during apartheid era, the ICC having placed a moratorium on tours of the country in 1970.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began the teams were split into two groups.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The ICC made the decision to place the two teams which were not Test playing countries in separate groups.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] They also decided to place England and Australia in separate groups and to do the same with India and Pakistan.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Six grounds were used to host matches during the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The announcement of venues began on 26 July 1973 when the ICC announced that the tournament would be played, with Lord's as the venue for the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The remaining venues were announced on 5 November 1974, with the scheduling for the tournament announced alongside that for the five county cricket tournaments that would take place during the 1975 season.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Other than Lord's, which hosted only one group stage match, and The Oval which hosted three, each of the grounds was used for two matches during the group stage.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Headingley and The Oval were the grounds chosen for the two semi-finals.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the competition began each team named a squad of 14 players.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Heading into the first Cricket World Cup, the Ladbrokes betting agency had the West Indies as the favourites at 9–4.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was followed by England at 11–4 with Pakistan and Australia in third and fourth respectively.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] East Africa was last in the betting odds at 1500–1.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Before the tournament, most of the teams played in warm-up matches against English county teams to get used to the English conditions with most of the national teams getting wins.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only East Africa, Sri Lanka and India lost at least one warm-up match before the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia played in Canada, losing to Eastern Canada and drawing with Toronto, before heading to England.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Eight days before the World Cup, the ICC declared in a unanimous decision that any of the balls that went over a batsman's head would be called wide due to the fast short-pitched bowling.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 7 June with four matches being played.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The match at Lord's saw England deliver the highest score by a team in the 60 over match with 334 runs being scored.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Dennis Amiss top scored for the English with 137 from 147 balls helped by Keith Fletcher and Chris Old who each recorded a half-century.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Sunil Gavaskar batted through the entire innings for only 36 runs off 174 balls, prompting Gulabrai Ramchand to speculate that he was treating the match as batting practice.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australia opened their campaign with a win against Pakistan at Headingley with a 73-run victory.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to Dennis Lillee's five-wicket haul which brought Pakistan's hope of a win crashing down as they collapsed from 181 for four to be all out for 205.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Earlier, Ross Edwards top scored for Australia with 80 as he aided the Australians in getting 94 runs from the last 13 overs to bring Australia to 278 for seven from their 60 overs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other two matches saw easy wins for the West Indies and New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Glenn Turner, he occupied the crease during the whole New Zealand innings as he top scored with 171 as New Zealand won by 181 runs over East Africa.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies took a nine-wicket victory over Sri Lanka who became the first team to score under 100 runs in a One Day International.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Despite missing two players due to operation – Asif Iqbal – and examinations – Imran Khan – Pakistan was not fazed by the missing players in the second round of games with the team scoring 266 for seven from their 60 overs with standing captain Majid Khan top scoring for Pakistan with 60.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies fell to 166 for eight which included a period of three wickets for only 10 runs as Bernard Julien, Clive Lloyd and Keith Boyce all losing their wickets.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] But the last wicket pair of Deryck Murray and Andy Roberts stole the match away as the West Indies won by a wicket off the final over.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] On the field, Alan Turner scored a century as Australia ended with 328 with Sri Lanka falling 52 runs short as John Mason from *The Daily Telegraph* stated that they might not have many new admirers with their short ball stuff sending two Sri Lankan batsman to hospital.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Group A saw two convincing wins to England and India.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] At Trent Bridge, Keith Fletcher top scored for England with 131 as he guided the English to their second victory and going to the lead of the group table with an 80-run win over New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The other match in Group A saw 720 spectators observe India record a 10-wicket victory with Madan Lal taking three wickets for India, after East Africa were all-out for only 120.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the match sold out four days in advance, the West Indies took on Australia to see who would finish top of Group B.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the ball swinging in the air, the pair of Rod Marsh and Ross Edwards guided Australia to 192 with a 99-run partnership for the sixth wicket after Australia fell to 61/5.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, the West Indies went on to take a seven-wicket victory with Alvin Kallicharran top scoring with 78, which included a period of 31 runs of nine Dennis Lillee deliveries as the West Indies finished top of Group B.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan ended their tournament with a 192-run victory over Sri Lanka at Trent Bridge with half centuries to Zaheer Abbas, Majid Khan and Sadiq Mohammad.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In Group A, New Zealand sealed their spot in the semi-finals with a four-wicket victory over India off the back of a century from Glenn Turner as he hit twelve fours on his way to an unbeaten innings of 114.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Only Ramesh Sethi offered much resistance, lasting for 32 overs to score 30.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The knockout stage of the Cricket World Cup consisted of two single-elimination rounds leading to a final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] If the match was delayed due to rain there were two reserve days to play out the match.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The first semi-final was between England and Australia at Headingley.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] For Australia, their one change in bringing in Gary Gilmour for Ashley Mallett proved critical in booking Australia's spot into the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] This was due to the grassy pitch that both captains would criticise after the match.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After Australia elected to field first, Gilmour took six wickets for 14 runs as he had England at 37 for seven after he bowled his 12 overs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Mike Denness attempted to bring England back but would lose his wicket as England fell for 93.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In the run-chase, Australia collapsed to 39 for six before Gilmour partnered with Doug Walters as they chased the remaining runs to earn Australia a berth in the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The second semi-final was between the West Indies and New Zealand at The Oval.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Batting first, New Zealand reached 92 for only one loss at the lunch break.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After lunch though, they collapsed to 158 with Geoff Howarth top scoring for New Zealand with 51, while Bernard Julien was the top wicket taker with four wickets.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] The final match on 21 June was sold out three days beforehand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] With the West Indies being favourites for the match, they were asked by Ian Chappell to bat first and would go on to score 291 for eight wickets from 60 overs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] After being given a second chance from a Ross Edwards dropped chance at mid-wicket, Clive Lloyd went on to top score for the West Indies with 102.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Gary Gilmour was the best of the Australian bowlers with five wickets for 48 runs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In response, Ian Chappell scored a half-century to set up the foundation for Australia before three run-outs from the hands of Viv Richards put the pressure on Australia as they collapsed to 233 for nine.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] A final-wicket partnership of 41 from Dennis Lillee and Jeff Thomson brought Australia within 18 runs of victory.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] But a fifth run-out of the innings saw Australia bowled out for 274 and would see the West Indies win by 17 runs, claiming the first men's World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Glenn Turner of New Zealand ended the tournament as the leading run scorer for the 1975 edition with his 333 runs coming in four games which included an unbeaten 171 against East Africa, which was also the highest score of the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] In second place was English player Dennis Amiss with Pakistan's Majid Khan rounding out the top three.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Australian player Gary Gilmour was the tournament's leading wicket taker with 11 wickets from his two games, which included the best tournament figures in the semi-finals when he took six wickets for 14 against England.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1975-cricket-world-cup] Bernard Julien and Keith Boyce (both from the West Indies) finished in second place, both getting 10 wickets for the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The **Benson & Hedges World Series Cup** was a cricket tournament held in Australia from 27 November 1979 to 22 January 1980.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] It was a tri-nations series featuring Australia, England and the West Indies, with all of the matches being played as One Day Internationals (ODI).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The series was part of the English and West Indian tour and was the first official tri-nations series after World Series Cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] After the round-robin matches which were played at four venues in Adelaide, Brisbane, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and the West Indies reached the final where the West Indies won the final series 2–0.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] The red ball was used and the white pads were worn for the matches in Adelaide, Brisbane and Melbourne, and the white ball was used and the coloured pads were worn for the matches in Sydney.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-80-australia-tri-nation-series] England and West Indies would not contest the tri-series again until the 1986-87 season.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The **1979 Cricket World Cup** (officially called the **Prudential Cup '79**) was the second edition of the Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Organised by the International Cricket Conference, it was held in England from 9 to 23 June 1979.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The tournament was once again sponsored by the Prudential Assurance Company and had eight teams participating in the tournament with the only change being Canada who qualified with Sri Lanka in the qualifier for the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The format remained the same with two teams qualifying from each group with the final once again being at Lord's.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England joined first-time semi-finalists Pakistan as the qualifiers from Group A, while the West Indies finished top of Group B ahead of New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] After the West Indies and England both won their semi-finals over Pakistan and New Zealand, respectively, they met in the final at Lord's with the West Indies defending their title from four years earlier with a 92-run victory.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] West Indian batsman, Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs from four matches with English player Mike Hendrick ending up as the leading wicket-taker with ten wickets.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The eight teams at the tournament were split into two groups of four teams, with each team playing the others in their group in a single round-robin format.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The top two teams from each group then advance to the semi-finals to play in a single-elimination tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 tournament saw the first qualifiers in a World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The 1979 ICC Trophy was held during late May and early June at various grounds in the English Midlands, with the two finalists qualifying for the World Cup where they joined the six Test nations who qualified automatically.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Sri Lanka and Canada qualified after defeating Denmark and Bermuda respectively in the semi-finals.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The opening round of matches took place on 9 June with four matches being played.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England took on Australia at Lord's and after the home team elected to field first, restricted the Australians to 97 for one with fine fielding and bowling.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] After Andrew Hilditch dragged his second ball after lunch into the stumps, the Australians would be restricted for 159 which included four run-outs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The run-chase saw Mike Brearley and Graham Gooch control the innings and led England to a six wicket victory.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] In a very close semi-final match, England prevailed.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England began badly, falling to 38/2, before Mike Brearley (53 from 115 balls, 3 fours) and Graham Gooch (71 from 84 balls, 1 four, 3 sixes) resurrected the innings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Derek Randall (42 from 50 balls, 1 four, 1 six) played well in the second half of the innings, as England recovered from 98/4 to post 221 (8 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] In the response, John Wright (69 from 137 balls) attacked well in the beginning.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of wickets bogged New Zealand down, and despite several late flourishes in the batting order, New Zealand started to drop behind.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] When New Zealand could not achieve the remaining 14 runs from the last over of the match, England went into the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge (73 from 107 balls, 5 fours, 1 six) and Desmond Haynes (65 from 115 balls, 4 fours) set a first wicket partnership of 132 runs in a match dominated by batting.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and Clive Lloyd also contributed solidly, as West Indies ran up 293 (6 wickets, 60 overs) against Pakistan.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Majid Khan (81 from 124 balls, 7 fours) and Zaheer Abbas (93 from 122 balls) shared a second-wicket partnership of 166 runs in 36 overs in the response.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, none of the other Pakistani batsmen flourished, with Javed Miandad being bowled for a duck first ball, and Pakistan lost 9/74, beginning with the dismissal of Abbas.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Pakistan was bowled out for 250 in 56.2 overs in the high-scoring semi-final, sending the West Indies to the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] England won the toss and chose to field first.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies got off to a bad start, falling to 99/4 with the loss of Greenidge, Haynes, Kallicharan, and captain Clive Lloyd.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, Vivian Richards (138 from 157 balls, 11 fours, 3 sixes) and Collis King (86 from 66 balls, 10 fours, 3 sixes) consolidated the innings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] King especially savaged the English bowling, with a strike rate of 130.3.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The West Indies were 238/5 when the 139 run partnership ended with King’s dismissal.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards and the tail then took the West Indies to a very imposing total of 286 (9 wickets, 60 overs).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The English batsmen got off to a good start.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] But the openers, Mike Brearley (64 from 130 balls, 7 fours) and Geoff Boycott (57 from 105 balls, 3 fours) scored very slowly with a methodical opening partnership of 129 runs in 38 overs, playing as if the match were a five-day Test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] By the time both batsmen were out, the required run rate had risen too high, putting pressure on the later batsmen.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch played some hefty strokes in scoring his 32, taking England to 183/2.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] However, the loss of Derek Randall triggered a batting collapse in which England lost their last eight wickets for 11 runs to finish all out for 194 in 51 overs.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Vivian Richards was declared Man of the Match.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Gordon Greenidge ended the tournament as the leading run scorer with 253 runs coming from his four games.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Second was fellow West Indian player, Viv Richards who finished with 217 runs from four games which included the highest individual score of the tournament of 138 in the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Graham Gooch from England rounded out the top three.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] Mike Hendrick from England was the leading wicket taker for the tournament with ten wickets from five matches with a three-way tie for second place with Brian McKechnie (New Zealand), Asif Iqbal (Pakistan) and Chris Old each taking nine wickets for the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/1979-cricket-world-cup] The total attendance at the tournament was 132,000, including 25,000 at the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The **Australia men's national cricket team** represents Australia in international cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team draws its players from teams playing in the Australian domestic competitions – the Sheffield Shield, the Australian domestic limited-overs cricket tournament and the Big Bash League.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia are the current ICC Cricket World Cup champions.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] They are generally regarded as the most successful national team in the history of cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The national team has played 882 Test matches, winning 426, losing 235, 219 drawn and with 2 tied.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] As of October 2025, Australia is first in the ICC Test Rankings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia is the most successful team in Test cricket history, in terms of overall wins, win–loss ratio, and wins percentage.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia have won the ICC World Test Championship once, defeating India in the final of the 2021–2023 World Test Championship.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Test rivalries centre on The Ashes (with England), the Border–Gavaskar Trophy (with India), the Frank Worrell Trophy (with the West Indies), the Trans-Tasman Trophy (with New Zealand), and matches against South Africa.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team has played 1,025 ODI matches, winning 619, losing 362, tying 9 and with 35 ending in a no-result.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] As of February 2026, Australia is ranked third in the ICC Men's ODI Team Rankings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia is the only team to appear in four consecutive World Cup finals (1996, 1999, 2003, and 2007), surpassing the old record of three consecutive World Cup appearances by the West Indies (1975, 1979, and 1983) and the only team to win three consecutive World Cups (1999, 2003, and 2007).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team was undefeated in 34 consecutive World Cup matches until the 2011 Cricket World Cup where Pakistan beat them by four wickets in the Group stage.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia is also the second team to win a World Cup (2015) on home soil, after India (2011).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia have also won the ICC Champions Trophy twice (2006 and 2009) making them the only team to be back-to-back winners in the Champions Trophy tournaments.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia has played 229 Twenty20 International matches, winning 127, losing 92, tying 3, and with 7 ending in a no-result.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] As of November 2025, Australia is ranked second in the ICC Men's T20I Team Rankings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia have won the ICC Men's T20 World Cup once, defeating New Zealand in the 2021 Final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] On 12 January 2019, Australia won an ODI against India at the Sydney Cricket Ground by 34 runs, to record their 1,000th win in international cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The Australian cricket team participated in the first Test match at the MCG in 1877.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] They defeated England by 45 runs, with Charles Bannerman making the first Test century with a score of 165.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Test cricket, which only occurred between Australia and England at the time, was limited by the long distance between the two countries, which took several months by sea.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Despite Australia's much smaller population, the team was very competitive in early games, producing stars such as Jack Blackham, Billy Murdoch, Fred "The Demon" Spofforth, George Bonnor, Percy McDonnell, George Giffen, and Charles "The Terror" Turner.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Most cricketers at the time were either from New South Wales or Victoria, with the notable exception of George Giffen, the star South Australian all-rounder.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] One of the highlights of Australia's early history was the 1882 Test match against England, which took place at The Oval.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In this match, Fred Spofforth took 7/44 in the game's fourth innings, saving the match by preventing England from making their 85-run target.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] To this day, the contest is one of the fiercest rivalries in sport.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The 'Golden Age' of Australian Test cricket occurred around the end of the 19th century, concluding at the beginning of the 20th century, with the team under the captaincy of Joe Darling, Monty Noble and Clem Hill, winning eight of ten tours.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] It is considered to have lasted from the 1897–98 English tour of Australia and the 1910–11 South African tour of Australia.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Outstanding batsmen such as Joe Darling, Clem Hill, and Reggie Duff, all helped Australia to become the dominant cricketing nation for most of this period.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Victor Trumper became one of Australia's first sporting heroes, who was widely considered Australia's greatest batsman before Bradman became one of the most popular players.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He played a record (at the time) of a number of Tests at 49, and scored 3163 runs at a high for the time average of 39.04.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He died in 1915 at the age of 37 from kidney disease, causing national mourning.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] This led to six leading players (the so-called "Big Six") walking out on the 1912 Triangular Tournament in England, with Australia fielding what was generally considered a second-rate team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] This was the last series before the war, and no more cricket was played by Australia for eight years.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Fast bowler Tibby Cotter, who had caused outrage with his bowling during the 1905 tour of England, after first striking W.G.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Grace with the ball, before dismissing him the following delivery, was killed during the Battle of Beersheba.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Test cricket resumed in the 1920/21 season in Australia with a touring English team captained by Johnny Douglas losing all five Tests to Australia, captained by the "Big Ship" Warwick Armstrong.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team continued its success on the 1921 tour of England, winning three out of the five Tests in Warwick Armstrong's last series.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team was, on the whole, inconsistent in the latter half of the 1920s, losing its first home Ashes series since the 1911–12 season in 1928–29.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The 1930 tour of England heralded a new age of success for the Australian team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team, led by Bill Woodfull – the "Great Un-bowlable" – featured legends of the game including Bill Ponsford, Stan McCabe, Clarrie Grimmett and the young pair of Archie Jackson and Don Bradman.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Bradman was the outstanding batsman of the series, scoring a record 974 runs, including one century, two double centuries and one triple century, a massive score of 334 at Leeds which including 309 runs in a day.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Jackson died of tuberculosis at the age of 23 three years later, after playing eight Tests.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team was widely considered unstoppable, winning nine of its next ten Tests.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The tactic, although effective, was widely considered by Australian crowds as vicious and unsporting.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Injuries to Bill Woodfull, who was struck over the heart, and Bert Oldfield, who received a fractured skull (although from a non-bodyline ball), exacerbated the situation, almost causing a full-scale riot from the 50 000 fans at the Adelaide Oval for the third Test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The conflict almost escalated into a diplomatic incident between the two countries, as leading Australian political figures, including the Governor of South Australia, Alexander Hore-Ruthven, protested to their English counterparts.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The series ended in a 4–1 win for England but the bodyline tactics used were banned the year after.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The Australian team put the result of this series behind them, winning their next tour of England in 1934.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team was led by Bill Woodfull on his final tour and was notably dominated by Ponsford and Bradman, who twice put on partnerships of over 380 runs, with Bradman once again scoring a triple century at Leeds.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The bowling was dominated by the spin pair of Bill O'Reilly and Clarrie Grimmett, who took 53 wickets between them, with O'Reilly twice taking seven-wicket hauls.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Sir Donald Bradman is widely considered the greatest player of all time.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He dominated the sport from 1930 until his retirement in 1948, setting new records for the highest score in a Test innings (334 vs England at Headingley in 1930), the most runs (6996), the most centuries (29), the most double centuries and the highest Test and first-class batting averages.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] His record for the highest Test batting average – 99.94 – has never been beaten.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] It is almost 40 runs per innings above the next highest average.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He would have finished with an average of over 100 runs per innings if he had not been dismissed for a duck in his last Test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He was knighted in 1949 for services to cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] He is generally considered one of Australia's all-time greatest sporting heroes, if not the greatest.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Test cricket was again interrupted by war, with the last Test series in 1938 made notable by Len Hutton scoring a world record 364 for England, and with Chuck Fleetwood-Smith conceding 298 runs in England's world record total of 7/903.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Ross Gregory, a notable young batsman who played two Tests before the war, was killed in the war.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team continued its success after the end of the Second World War with the first Test (also Australia's first against New Zealand) being played in the 1945–46 season against New Zealand.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia was by far the most successful team of the 1940s, being undefeated throughout the decade, winning two Ashes series against England and its first Test series against India.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The team that Don Bradman led to England in 1948 gained the moniker *The Invincibles*, after going through the tour without losing a single game.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Of 31 first-class games played during the tour, they won 23 and drew 8, including winning the five-match Test series 4–0 with one draw.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] However, the team rebounded to win five consecutive series in the latter half of the 1950s, first under the leadership of Ian Johnson, then Ian Craig and Richie Benaud.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The series against the West Indies in the 1960–61 season was notable for the Tied Test in the first game at the Gabba, which was the first in Test cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia ended up winning the series 2–1 after a hard-fought series that was praised for its excellent standards and sense of fair play.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The Centenary Test was played in March 1977 at the MCG to celebrate 100 years since the first Test was played.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia won the match by 45 runs, an identical result to the first Test match.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In May 1977, Kerry Packer announced he was organising a breakaway competition – World Series Cricket (WSC) – after the Australian Cricket Board (ACB) refused to accept Channel Nine's bid to gain exclusive television rights to Australia's Test matches in 1976.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Packer secretly signed leading international cricketers to his competition, including 28 Australians.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Almost all of the Australian Test team at the time were signed to WSC – notable exceptions including Gary Cosier, Geoff Dymock, Kim Hughes and Craig Serjeant – and the Australian selectors were forced to pick what was generally considered a third-rate team from players in the Sheffield Shield.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Former player Bob Simpson, who had retired 10 years previously after a conflict with the board, was recalled at the age of 41 to captain Australia against India.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Jeff Thomson was named deputy in a team that included seven debutants.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia managed to win the series 3–2, mainly thanks to the batting of Simpson, who scored 539 runs, including two centuries; and the bowling of Wayne Clark, who took 28 wickets.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia lost the next series 3–1 against the West Indies, which was fielding a full strength team; and also lost the 1978–79 Ashes series 5–1, the team's worst Ashes result in Australia.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Graham Yallop was named as captain for the Ashes, with Kim Hughes taking over for the 1979–80 tour of India.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Rodney Hogg took 41 wickets in his debut series, an Australian record.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] WSC players returned to the team for the 1979–80 season after a settlement between the ACB and Kerry Packer.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Greg Chappell was reinstated as captain.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The underarm bowling incident of 1981 occurred when, in an ODI against New Zealand, Greg Chappell instructed his brother Trevor to bowl an underarm delivery to New Zealand batsman Brian McKechnie with New Zealand needing a six to tie off the last ball.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The aftermath of the incident soured political relations between Australia and New Zealand, with several leading political and cricketing figures calling it "unsportsmanlike" and "not in the spirit of cricket".
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia continued its success up until the early 1980s, built around the Chappell brothers, Dennis Lillee, Jeff Thomson and Rod Marsh.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The 1980s was a period of relative mediocrity after the turmoil caused by the Rebel Tours of South Africa and the subsequent retirement of several key players.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The rebel tours were funded by the South African Cricket Board to compete against its national team, which had been banned—along with many other sports, including Olympic athletes—from competing internationally, due to the South African government's racist apartheid policies.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Some of Australia's best players were poached: Graham Yallop, Carl Rackemann, Terry Alderman, Rodney Hogg, Kim Hughes, John Dyson, Greg Shipperd, Steve Rixon and Steve Smith amongst others.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] These players were handed three-year suspensions by the Australian Cricket Board which greatly weakened the player pool for the national teams, as most were either current representative players or on the verge of gaining honours.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The so-called 'Golden Era' of Australian cricket occurred around the end of the 20th century and the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] This was a period in which Australian cricket recovered from the disruption caused by World Series Cricket to create arguably the strongest Test team in history.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Under the captaincy of Allan Border and the new fielding standards put in place by new coach Bob Simpson, the team was restructured and gradually rebuilt their cricketing stocks.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Some of the rebel players returned to the national team after serving their suspensions, including Trevor Hohns, Carl Rackemann and Terry Alderman.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] During these lean years, it was the batsmen Border, David Boon, Dean Jones, the young Steve Waugh and the bowling feats of Alderman, Bruce Reid, Craig McDermott, Merv Hughes and to a lesser extent, Geoff Lawson who kept the Australian team afloat.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] With the emergence of players such as Ian Healy, Mark Taylor, Geoff Marsh, Mark Waugh, and Greg Matthews in the late 1980s, Australia was on the way back from the doldrums.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] They went on to win their first ever world title by getting the better of England in the 1987 Cricket World Cup final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Winning the Ashes in 1989, the Australians got a roll on beating Pakistan, Sri Lanka and then followed it up with another Ashes win on home soil in 1991.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The Australians went on to the West Indies and had their chances but ended up losing the series.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] However, they bounced back and beat the Indians in their next Test series; with the retirement of the champion but defensive Allan Border, a new era of attacking cricket had begun under the leadership of firstly Mark Taylor and then Steve Waugh.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia ended the 20th century by winning the 1999 Cricket World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The 1990s and early 21st century were arguably Australia's most successful periods, unbeaten in all Ashes series played bar the famous 2005 series and achieving a hat-trick of World Cups.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Following the 2006–07 Ashes series which Australia won 5–0, Australia slipped in the rankings after the retirements of key players.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In the 2013/14 Ashes series, Australia again defeated England 5–0 and climbed back to third in the ICC International Test rankings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In February/March 2014, Australia beat South Africa, the number one team in the world, 2–1 and overtook them to return to the top of the rankings.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2015, Australia won the Cricket World Cup, losing just one game for the tournament.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] On 25 March 2018, during the third Test match against hosts South Africa; players Cameron Bancroft, Steve Smith, David Warner and the leadership group of the team were implicated in a ball tampering scandal.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Smith and Bancroft admitted to conspiring to alter the condition of the ball by rubbing it with a piece of adhesive tape containing abrasive granules picked up from the ground (it was later revealed that sandpaper was used).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Smith stated that the purpose was to gain an advantage by unlawfully changing the ball's surface in order to generate reverse swing.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Bancroft had been filmed tampering with the ball and, after being informed he had been caught, he was seen to transfer a yellow object from a pocket to the inside front of his trousers to hide the evidence.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Steve Smith and David Warner were stood down as captain and vice-captain during the third Test while head coach, Darren Lehmann was suspected to have assisted Cameron Bancroft to tamper the ball.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The ICC imposed a one-match ban and 100%-match-fee fine on Smith, while Bancroft was fined 75 percent of his match fee and received 3 demerit points.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Smith and Warner were both stripped of their captaincy roles by Cricket Australia and sent home from the tour (along with Bancroft).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Tim Paine was appointed as captain for the fourth Test.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket Australia then suspended Smith and Warner from playing for 12 months and Bancroft for 9 months.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Smith and Bancroft could not be considered for leadership roles for 12 months after the suspension, while Warner is banned from leadership of any Cricket Australia team for life.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In the aftermath of these events, Darren Lehmann announced his resignation as head coach at the end of the series, with Justin Langer replacing him.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] On 8 May 2018, Tim Paine was also named as the ODI captain while Aaron Finch was reinstated as T20I captain hours later, although Finch replaced Paine as the ODI captain after the 5–0 ODI series whitewash in England in June 2018.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] On 7 October 2018, Australia played their first Test match under new coach Justin Langer and a new leadership group, which included Tim Paine as Australia's 46th Test captain.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] After a 1–0 loss to Pakistan in a two match Test series against Pakistan in the UAE and a 2–1 defeat against India in a four match Test series, they found success against Sri Lanka, winning the two Test match series 2–0.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2019, Australia played in the Cricket World Cup, where they finished second in the group stage before being knocked out by England at Edgbaston in the semi-final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia later went on to retain the Ashes during the 2019 Ashes series, the first time on English soil since 2001, by winning the fourth Test at Old Trafford.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2020–21, Australia hosted India for 3 ODIs, 3 T20Is, and 4 Tests.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] They won the ODI series 2–1, but lost the T20I series 2–1.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Then, the two teams competed for the Border–Gavaskar Trophy which saw one of the greatest overseas Test triumphs by India in the 4th Test to win the series 2–1, with the 3rd Test being drawn.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In 2021, Australia named a 15-member squad for the upcoming T20 World Cup with regular limited overs captain Aaron Finch leading the team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In finals, they would face their trans-Tasman rivals New Zealand and win the match to claim their maiden T20 World Cup Trophy.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] On 19 November 2021, Tim Paine resigned from the captaincy due to off-the-field misconduct, and was replaced by Pat Cummins, who became Australia's 47th Test captain, with Steve Smith named as his deputy.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Under Pat Cummins, Australia retained 2021–22 Ashes at home by winning the series 4–0.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia then toured Pakistan in March 2022 for the first time since 1998 to play 3 test matches and 3 ODIs and one-off T20.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia failed to advance to knockouts in 2022 T20 World Cup.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Australia's white ball captain Finch retired from international cricket.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Afterwards, Pat Cummins was made ODI captain.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Under Cummins’ captaincy, Australia had a stellar 2023, winning their maiden ICC World Test Championship title (which made them the first team in history to win all major ICC Trophies across all formats), and retaining the Ashes on their tour to England.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In November, they won the 2023 Cricket World Cup, defeating the host India in the final.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] For Test matches, the team wears cricket whites, with an optional sweater or sweater-vest, with a green and gold V-neck for use in cold weather.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The sponsor's (currently Westpac for home matches and Qantas for away matches) logo is displayed on the right side of the chest while the Cricket Australia emblem is displayed on the left.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] If the sweater is being worn the Cricket Australia emblem is displayed under the V-neck and the sponsor's logo is again displayed on the right side of the chest.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The baggy green, the Australian Test cricket cap, is considered an essential part of the cricketing uniform and as a symbol of the national team, with new players being presented with one upon their selection in the team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The cap and the helmet both prominently display the Australian cricketing coat-of-arms instead of the Cricket Australia emblem.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] At the end of 2011, ASICS was named the manufacturer of the whites and limited over uniforms from Adidas, with the ASICS logo being displayed on the shirt and pants.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Players may choose any manufacturer for their other gear (bat, pads, shoes, gloves, etc.).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] In One Day International (ODI) cricket and Twenty20 International cricket, the team wears uniforms usually coloured green and gold, the national colours of Australia.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] There has been a variety of different styles and layouts used in both forms of the limited-overs game, with coloured clothing (sometimes known as "pyjamas") being introduced for World Series Cricket in the late 1970s.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The Toyota or Qantas logo is prominently displayed on the shirts and other gears.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The current T20I kit consists of green as the primary colour and gold as the secondary colour.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] The ODI is the opposite of the T20I kit, with gold as the primary colour and green as the secondary colour.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] However, since Australia beat New Zealand at the MCG in the 2015 Cricket World Cup wearing the gold uniform, it has also become their primary colour, with the hats used being called 'floppy gold', formerly known as 'baggy gold', a limited-overs equivalent to a baggy green.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Until the early 2000s and briefly in early 2020, in ODIs, Australia wore yellow helmets, before using green helmets as in test matches.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Before Travelex (and 3 in test matches), some of the former sponsors were XXXX (1990–1992), Coca-Cola (1993–1998), Fly Emirates (1999) and Carlton & United Breweries (2000–2001).
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Cricket Australia announced its list of centrally contracted players for the 2026–27 season on 1 April 2026.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Players can be upgraded to national contracts throughout the year by earning 12 upgrade points, with a Test worth five points and each ODI and T20I worth two.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p01] Players without international caps are listed in *italics*.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] Test Cricket features multiple trophies competed for when teams play one another in a Test series.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] Australia contests a trophy with seven other Test nations, currently holding all seven.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The team song is "Under the Southern Cross I Stand", which is sung by the players after every victory and "treated with reverential consideration and respect" within the team.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The official lyrics are as follows, though when it is sung by the players, the word "little" in the last line is instead replaced by "bloody" or the expletive "fucking".
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The authorship of this "Under the Southern Cross I Stand" is credited to former wicketkeeper Rod Marsh, who was apparently inspired by Henry Lawson's 1887 poem, "Flag of the Southern Cross".
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] Marsh initially had the role of leading the team in singing it and, on his retirement, passed it on to Allan Border.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] With Nathan Lyon's departure from the team due to injury after the Second Ashes Test at Lord's in 2023, custody of the song has passed to wicketkeeper Alex Carey.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] Since the 1990s, team members have identified themselves or their teammates as either "nerds" or "Julios".
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The "nerds" have cheap haircuts, are polite off-field, and let their playing performance define them.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The Julios have fashionable hairstyles and wear snappy clothes.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] The term "Julio" is reported to refer to Spanish singer Julio Iglesias.
[src:australia-national-cricket-team/australia-national-cricket-team-p02] In a 2016 podcast, Australian fast bowler Josh Hazlewood wrote that the "nerds" tended to be fast bowlers, and gave himself as an example.
